summary: I was originally upset with how things ended for him but this edit really puts it into perspective. Tyrion said that it was...
caption:
I was originally upset with how things ended for him but this edit really puts it into perspective. Tyrion said that it was Jaime who accepted him no matter what, and it was also Jaime who saw the “monster” in Cersei and loved her anyway. That’s why we like and respond to him. His redemption wouldn’t have been living out his days with a big fat glorious label of “honourable” slapped on him. He killed and betrayed and fought for Cersei, and at the same time he was always helping Tyrion escape and so on. We’ve always thought he was good when he was protecting Tyrion and evil when he was protecting Cersei and her interests. If we think about it, from a complete outsider’s point of view both sets of actions are selfish and backward but the real common denominator is exactly as above, family. 

It’s not a coincidence in the last episode that Tyrion tells him to escape like Jaime had tried to do for him. Even after everything, Tyrion has ended up back at Kings Landing anyway and he’s now prepared to face any punishment Daenerys sets on him. This is the same with Jaime, he’s come full circle— he’s facing his crimes. We might ask why he’s protecting Cersei at a moment like this. But that’s just it. He has always seen the bad in her, and he has a tumultuous relationship with that. Way back when, people expected him to go on protecting Aerys even when he was going mad, but now that he’s protecting Cersei we think he’s mad. It’s the same on paper— he’s keeping his promise to protect and love someone no matter what they’ve done. He’s done it at the “wrong” moment in history, and people can only know him as a traitor, but this just questions what being a knight really means. And that’s what Jaime Lannister has always been about.We want him to kill Cersei or whatever but that’s because we want him to be the songs-and-tales good knight. It’s because he was on the way to becoming one. But how it’s ended with him now is Jaime as an actual “good” knight, that is, someone who continuously makes choices based on loyalty. They showed us with Ned Stark that it can be stupid. They showed us with Brienne it can be good but complicated— she was accused of killing Renly, she was seen for being a Lannister sympathiser, etc etc. And now they’ve showed us with Jaime that it’s rarely ever simple. 

The way they wrote his scenes with Cersei were fine. But I think the crux of the misunderstanding is when he said he never cared about the people in Kings Landing anyway. I think that should have been a bigger moment so that all of this about Jaime really came to light for the audience, and the key point, that most importantly he would never kill Tywin no matter what, would have come through. He died completely on his own terms and of his own choices. RIP.﻿

summary: a thank you to all the cast and crew of Game of Thrones
body:
a thank you to all the cast and crew of Game of Thrones

Ngl with all the things I don’t agree with in the finale season of got - I’ve enjoyed myself

the props/sets/special effects/makeup/wardrobe/acting/soundtrack/cinematography/and acting (saying it twice) have been incredible.

(I’ve also really enjoyed the memes)

I will be binge watching from season 1 after next week.

And as I stand back and look at s8… I’m not as disappointed as I first thought

I will miss this series

Thank you to all those who spent hours upon hours and years upon years making got come to life

Y’all were fab
